It takes a lot of courage to go to war. It takes even more when you have to hide part of who you are. My new plan will review & upgrade the 100,000+ servicemembers who have been less-than-honorably discharged since World War II for sexual orientation or <U+201C>homosexual activity." https://t.co/Kpy2NblMcO

For too long, our country has discriminated against LGBTQ veterans who put their lives on the line for our freedom. It<U+2019>s time to fix this injustice for good, and that<U+2019>s exactly what I will do as President.

The review boards will then ensure upgraded veterans understand their new benefits, and in the case of deceased veterans, the military records of individual servicemembers will be updated to reflect the change to honorable discharge.

The military record correction & discharge review boards will examine the discharge status to determine who was separated for sexual orientation. Unless the military provides records to justify the discharge on other grounds, each veteran<U+2019>s status will be upgraded to honorable.

Since the repeal of DADT, servicemembers have been able to appeal their discharge status<U+2014>but the burden of initiating that review rests with the veteran. That burden should be on the government. As President, I<U+2019>m going to fix this injustice for good.

<U+2014> An other-than-honorable discharge can negatively affect a veteran<U+2019>s employment prospects. 
<U+2014> Veterans who receive something other than an honorable discharge are five to seven times more likely to fall into homelessness.

That<U+2019>s wrong, and it has real consequences: 
<U+2014> Anything other than an honorable discharge makes a veteran ineligible for GI Bill benefits & can negatively affect a veteran<U+2019>s ability to receive health benefits & disability claims.

I was proud to support President Barack Obama when he repealed the discriminatory policy in 2010. But the repeal didn't include retroactive upgrades for the more than 100,000 service members who had been less-than-honorably discharged since World War II because of who they are.

When I was in Iraq, the race, religion, or sexual orientation of my fellow Marines didn<U+2019>t matter. But <U+201C>Don<U+2019>t Ask, Don<U+2019>t Tell<U+201D> discriminated against some of the bravest Americans I<U+2019>ve ever met, forcing them to choose between service & being open about who they are.
LGBTQ military members have served our country honorably for decades. It's time they all get the recognition they deserve. https://t.co/37ZVBueLz2
